description.narrative:
An external evaluation of the multi-donor Governance Trust Fund (GTF) was conducted to assess the GTF’s achievement over the first three years of implementation (2011-2014). Some of the key achievements of the different projects across the continent which were funded through the Bank’s grant (as identified by the evaluation) include; • The Government of Togo has been successfully supported in its decision to launch a Single Revenue Agency (Togo);
• The capacity of civil society in Africa to engage in economic and financial governance, in particular public procurement, corporate social responsibility, and domestic revenue mobilisation(AGI) has been strengthened;
• The Tunisia scoping study, involving data collection from 450 associations throughout the country, has generated better knowledge and understanding of citizen participation in social service delivery;
• In Kenya, the capacity of local officials from 47 counties in budgeting and audit processes has been strengthened; and 
• Malawi Construction Sector Transparency Initiative (CoST), through multistakeholder engagement and the validation of the assurance Report, provided a solid foundation to promote the disclosure of critical information in the construction sector.Moreover, the review concluded that in addition to the above intended results, the GTF projects resulted in strengthening the Bank’s own capacity in economic and financial governance. It has helped the Bank to particularly;
• enhance its credibility with, and gain greater knowledge of, CSOs and multi stakeholder groups (Tunisia, Malawi).• Build new platforms for dialogue.
• Increase its visibility and enhance dialogue with Development Partners and government.
